# Cloud workflow

Run autonomously unless the user is only asking a question.

**Setup and services:** follow **`README.md`**. Below is only what differs in the cloud environment.

## Environment

- Secrets come from the Cursor dashboard. **Do not** create `.env` files in the cloud.
- If env vars fail, notify the user and stop.
- All vars from `.env.example` must be set in the dashboard (use placeholders where needed; empty strings are not supported).
- If `pnpm check` misses `$env/static/*` exports, run `pnpm sync`.

## Cloud-only runtime (only if the project uses local services)

- Start Docker daemon before compose: `sudo dockerd &>/tmp/dockerd.log &`, then wait ~3s, then `docker compose up -d` (see README for services).
- Wait for Postgres `healthy` in `docker compose ps` before migrations or any worker.
- On a fresh Postgres volume, `docker compose down -v` may be needed before first migrate.
- Run a background worker in a separate process if the project has one (see README).
- First Vite SSR request can take ~15–18s; later requests are fast.

## Database migrations (non-interactive, only if the project uses Prisma)

`pnpm db:migrate:dev` prompts for a migration name. In cloud agents and CI, use:

```sh
# Create migration SQL from pending schema changes (no apply)
pnpm exec prisma migrate dev --name <descriptive_snake_case_name> --create-only

# Apply pending migrations
pnpm db:migrate:deploy
```

Use a short, descriptive migration name (e.g. `add_contact_source`, `drop_legacy_column`).

## Git and PRs

- Work on feature branches. Never push to `master`/`main`.
- Finish with an **open, ready-for-review PR** (not draft) unless the task was question-only.
- Before a write-capable subagent runs, be on a feature branch.
- PR titles start with a capital letter. Keep the description cumulative and current with all commits.
- For create/update/review flow, follow the `github-pull-requests` skill.
- **Before every `git commit`:** read the `git-commit-style` skill and follow it exactly. Always use the `git-commit-style` skill for writing the commit messages. If instructions conflict on commit messages, `git-commit-style` wins over generic "descriptive commit" wording.
- **Issue-driven PRs:** When work comes from a GitHub issue, the PR description must include a **References** section with `Closes #<number>` (linked to the issue) so the issue auto-closes on merge. Use proper capitalization.
- **Tagged on an issue:** Your final cloud output message is posted as the Cursor bot comment on the issue.
  The user usually does not see WIP messages, so end with a short summary, link to the open PR, and any blockers. Keep it concise.

## Verification gate

Before commit/push/PR update:

```bash
pnpm fix
pnpm check
pnpm build
```

Attach verification artifacts (screenshots/recordings) to the PR for user-visible changes.
